The CZ 75 SP-01 is the first full size handgun (4.72 bbl) from CZ to feature the improved manufacturing technology and ergonomics of the NATO approved CZ 75 Compact P-01 model. Featuring an integral 1913 accessory rail on the dust cover, rubber grip panels, and CZs corrosion resistant black polycoat finish, the SP-01 is the newest model to join the family of pistols based on the CZ 75 (SA/DA) platform. Borrowing from the improved grip geometry of the CZ 75 Compact P-01, the SP-01 utilizes an extended beaver tail to protect shooters strong hand as well as allowing for a deeper and more secure grip. The SP-01 was designed as a military and law enforcement duty sidearm. The new model is currently in use by security forces fighting the war on terrorism. Thanks to its exceptional accuracy and superior handling characteristics, the CZ 75 SP-01 has also found supporters in the field of sport and target shooting. title: For Sale/Trade:  1964 Remington Model 700 .222 MAG BDL 23.5" Barrel
postcontent:
**Trade Pending 12-11-15**

The coolest thing about this weapon and round it delivers is that the .222 is the father of the .223 we are all too familiar with. I received this weapon in a trade and I am looking to sell or trade it out for something different. Serial number is 108,XXX. The barrel date codes are "KL" which means it was manufactured in either 1942, 1964, or 1991. However, noting the pressed checkering design in the stock eliminates the 1991 year of manufacture as the design changed some time in the 70's. The model 700 line wasn't put into production until 1962 which rules out its date of 1942. To solidify its date of manufacture this weapon has a square shaped thumb safety. The 700's thumb safety was originally a square shape then changing it to a more rounded shape in 1969 making this rifle a 1964 year model 700 chambered in .222 MAG with a 23.5" barrel (rare). 

To note the BDL series this weapon has the traditional "trap door" style internal magazine, Blackened fore-end tip. blackened pistol grip butt plate, and blackened shoulder butt plate. Rifle also has the original leather sling with quick disconnects still in good shape. 

I would put this weapon at 90% due to a couple very minor dings on the butt stock and that the finish is vaguely cloudy in a few areas. This weapon has had minimal use, has a clean bore and appears to have been kept in a climate controlled area. 

Attached to the weapon is the original Bushnell Scope Chief which has clear glass and almost perfect finish. 

I work in Fredericksburg and live in Hampton Roads. I can meet almost anywhere but will need a couple days to get my affairs in order. 

Cash price is contingent upon your homework and offer. Will accept partial trades and cash combination. Can ship to FFL for an out of state purchase. 

Can send additional close up pictures upon request.

DISCLAIMER: I am not a business and do not pretend to know all of the high capacity laws for each state. I no longer own a 19, so these are the spares I purchased a while back. BUYER assumes all legal responsibility for adhering to their municipal, local, and state laws. Any questions please ask or inquire at your local gun shop or friendly police department. I have included below what I found on internet. If this has changed, buyer again needs to be aware of state laws where they reside. Thank you. [SEE BELOW: Six states and the District of Columbia (D.C.) currently ban or restrict large capacity magazines. Maryland defines a “large capacity magazine” as a magazine capable of accepting more than 20 rounds. New Jersey defines it as one capable of accepting more than 15 rounds, and California, Hawaii, Massachusetts, New York, and D.C. define it as a magazine capable of accepting more than 10 rounds. (On January 15, 2013, the NY Legislature amended its law. Beginning March 16, the law defines high capacity magazines as magazines capable of firing more than seven rounds.) In five states (California, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, and New York) and D.C., the ban applies to large capacity ammunition magazines used with any firearm. The Hawaii ban applies only to such magazines used with handguns. The Massachusetts ban exempts magazines lawfully possessed on September 13, 1994 (the date the federal ban took effect). New Jersey bans the possession, manufacture, transfer, and transportation of large capacity magazines, including pre- and post-ban magazines. New York bans these same activities and, beginning March 16, the ban will apply to all large capacity magazines, including ones previously grandfathered. (California effectively grandfathers the possession of pre-ban large capacity magazines by not outlawing possession of such magazines.) Thank you for looking.
